spec: io3436
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(io)
docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/io.html
provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/io.html — io: Core tools for working with streams"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 676 (io3436): __le__, __gt__, __ge__ dict-presence checks for io types."
    - "Classes covered: io.RawIOBase, io.BufferedIOBase, io.TextIOBase, io.FileIO, io.BytesIO, io.StringIO, io.BufferedReader, io.BufferedWriter, io.BufferedRandom, io.BufferedRWPair, io.TextIOWrapper."
    - "Theme: __le__/__gt__/__ge__ dict-presence (x<=y, x>y, x>=y)."
    - "No io class defines __le__ in its own __dict__: io stream classes are sequential I/O abstractions; <= is not explicitly defined on any io class."
    - "No io class defines __gt__ in its own __dict__: io stream classes do not implement ordering in their own __dict__s."
    - "No io class defines __ge__ in its own __dict__: io stream classes do not implement ordering in their own __dict__s."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Consistent with prior waves: all ordering operators absent from io class __dict__s."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"
error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __le__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__le__')
#
# No io class defines __le__ in its own __dict__; all false.
# io stream classes are sequential I/O abstractions, not ordered types,
# and do not implement the <= operator in their own __dict__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

